\begin_layout Standard
We will define an environment of order 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 as a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{E}_{N}:=\overset{N}{\underset{i=0}{\bigcup}}\mathcal{E}_{i}$
\end_inset

 wich defines a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a set must satisfy the following properties: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\mathbb{Z}^{2}=\mathfrak{E}_{\infty}\right)\bigwedge\left[\left(\mathcal{E}_{i}\bigcap\mathcal{E}_{j}=\phi\right)\iff\left(i\ne j\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

For the purpose of this document, we will restric the way of constructing
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{i}$
\end_inset

 subsets:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\#\mathcal{E}_{i}<\infty
\]

\end_inset

we will only allow those ones with a finite number of elements inside.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let's define a basis set 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left\{ \boldsymbol{s}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\right\} _{i=1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and a pattern 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}=\left\{ \boldsymbol{r}_{i}\in\left(\underset{[0,1)}{\mathcal{L}}(S)\oplus\mathbb{R}\right)\right\} _{i=1}^{Q}$
\end_inset

 .
 With these tools we can generate the collection of elements of a periodic
 periodic surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{S}$
\end_inset

 with pattern 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{S}\left(\mathfrak{P}\right)=\left\{ \boldsymbol{w}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\,:\,\boldsymbol{w}=\boldsymbol{t}+\boldsymbol{r}\,,\,\boldsymbol{r}\in\mathfrak{P}\,,\,\boldsymbol{t}\in\underset{\mathbb{Z}}{\mathcal{L}(S)}\right\} \,;\,\#\mathfrak{S}\left(\mathfrak{P}\right)=\aleph_{0}
\]

\end_inset

which means that each element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{S}\left(\mathfrak{P}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be generated as the sum of a linear combination (with integer coefficients)
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 vectors and one element of the pattern set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{t}\in\underset{\mathbb{Z}}{\mathcal{L}(S)}$
\end_inset

 can be written as: 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{t}=\underline{n}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{n}\in\mathbb{Z}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We can define the equivalence relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $\diamond$
\end_inset

 given elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w},\boldsymbol{v}\in\mathfrak{S}(\mathfrak{P})$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{t},\boldsymbol{q}\in\underset{\mathbb{Z}}{\mathcal{L}(S)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}\in\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{w}\diamond\boldsymbol{v}\,\implies\,\left(\boldsymbol{w}=\boldsymbol{t}+\boldsymbol{r}\right)\bigwedge\left(\boldsymbol{v}=\boldsymbol{q}+\boldsymbol{r}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which defines the class 
\begin_inset Formula $[i]_{\diamond}=\left\{ \boldsymbol{w}\in\mathfrak{S}(\mathfrak{P})\,:\,\boldsymbol{w}\diamond\boldsymbol{r}_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{S}(\mathfrak{P})$
\end_inset

.
 Of course:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\mathfrak{S}\left(\mathfrak{P}\right)=\underset{i=1}{\overset{Q}{\bigcup}}\left[i\right]_{\diamond}\right)\bigwedge\left(\#\left[i\right]_{\diamond}=\aleph_{0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Extraction of corrugation with 1D functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to calculate the interaction of a given atom with a periodic
 surface with pattern 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

, we can use the tools presented in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Definitions"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider that it exists a set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{i}\}_{i=1}^{L}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{array}{cccc}
f_{i}\,: & \mathbb{R}^{3}\otimes\mathfrak{S}\left(\mathfrak{P}\right) & \longrightarrow & \mathbb{R}\\
 & \left(\boldsymbol{p},\boldsymbol{w}\right) & \longrightarrow & f_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{p},\boldsymbol{w}\right)
\end{array}$
\end_inset

 which contains the interaction between an atom at position 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 with a pattern of nature 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}\in\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

.
 They define a new equivalence relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{i}{\star}$
\end_inset

, given elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}\in\mathfrak{S}\left(\mathfrak{P}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{x}\underset{i}{\star}\boldsymbol{y}\,\implies\left(\forall\boldsymbol{t}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\right)\left(f(\boldsymbol{t},\boldsymbol{x})=f(\boldsymbol{t},\boldsymbol{y})=f_{i}(\boldsymbol{t},\boldsymbol{r}_{i})\right)
\]

\end_inset

and therefore, the class:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[i]_{\star}=\left\{ \boldsymbol{w}\in\mathfrak{S}(\mathfrak{P})\,:\,\boldsymbol{w}\star\boldsymbol{r}_{i}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

Usually, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[i\right]_{\star}=\left[i\right]_{\diamond}$
\end_inset

 , but there are cases in which we have to set two atoms of the same type
 in the pattern.
 That yields to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[i\right]_{\star}\ne\left[i\right]_{\diamond}$
\end_inset

 .
 An interaction function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 commonly satisfies the following statements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\delta\rightarrow\infty}{\lim}f_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{p},\boldsymbol{w}\right)=a<\infty$
\end_inset

, being 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 the distance from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience, it is good to chose 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 is not linear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the interaction with a given surface have infinite terms, we will use
 the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{E_{\infty}}$
\end_inset

 in order to truncate the series.
 In general, the total interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{array}{cccc}
F\,: & \mathbb{R}^{3} & \longrightarrow & \mathbb{R}\\
 & \left(\boldsymbol{p}\right) & \longrightarrow & F\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)
\end{array}$
\end_inset

 can be written:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)=\overset{L}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\underset{\forall\boldsymbol{w}\in\left[i\right]_{\star}}{\sum}f_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{p},\boldsymbol{w}\right)=\overset{L}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\left(\underset{\forall\boldsymbol{r}\in\left[i\right]_{\star}\bigcap\mathfrak{P}}{\sum}\right)\underset{\forall\underline{n}\in\mathbb{Z}^{2}}{\sum}f_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\,,\,\underline{n}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\boldsymbol{r}\right)
\]

\end_inset

thus, we can define the truncated interaction at order 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)=\overset{L}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\left(\underset{\forall\boldsymbol{r}\in\left[i\right]_{\star}\bigcap\mathfrak{P}}{\sum}\right)\underset{\forall\underline{n}\in\mathfrak{E}_{N}}{\sum}f_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\,,\,\underline{n}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\boldsymbol{r}\right)
\]

\end_inset

or expanded:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)=\overset{L}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\left(\underset{\forall\boldsymbol{r}\in\left[i\right]_{\star}\bigcap\mathfrak{P}}{\sum}\right)\left\{ \underset{\forall\underline{n}\in\mathcal{E}_{1}}{\sum}\ldots\underset{\forall\underline{n}\in\mathcal{E}_{N}}{\sum}f_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\,,\,\underline{n}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\boldsymbol{r}\right)\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

the common condition
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left[i\right]_{\star}=\left[i\right]_{\diamond}\right)$
\end_inset

 simplifies the equation to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)=\overset{Q}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\left\{ \underset{\forall\underline{n}\in\mathcal{E}_{0}}{\sum}\ldots\underset{\forall\underline{n}\in\mathcal{E}_{N}}{\sum}f_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\,,\,\underline{n}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\boldsymbol{r}_{i}\right)\right\} \label{eq:general clases equal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Environment with square/rectangular partition of space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{E}_{i}^{<8>}=\begin{cases}
\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}\right\}  & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i=0\end{array}\\
\overset{i}{\underset{k=-i}{\bigcup}}\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}i\\
k
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}-i\\
k
\end{pmatrix}\right\} \overset{i-1}{\underset{k=-i+1}{\bigcup}}\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}k\\
i
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}k\\
-i
\end{pmatrix}\right\}  & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i\in\mathbb{N}^{+}\end{array}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

We can easily calculate the cardinal of each subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{i}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\#\mathcal{E}_{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i=0\end{array}\\
8i & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i\in\mathbb{N}^{+}\end{array}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's apply the general equation Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general clases equal"

\end_inset

 to this specific case:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{N}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right) & = & \overset{Q}{\underset{j=1}{\sum}}f_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{p},\boldsymbol{r}_{j}\right)+\overset{Q}{\underset{j=1}{\sum}}\overset{N}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\overset{i}{\underset{k=-i}{\sum}}\left\{ f_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{p},\begin{bmatrix}i\\
k
\end{bmatrix}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\boldsymbol{r}_{j}\right)+f_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{p},\begin{bmatrix}-i\\
k
\end{bmatrix}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\boldsymbol{r}_{j}\right)\right\} +\\
 &  & +\overset{Q}{\underset{j=1}{\sum}}\overset{N}{\underset{i=1}{\sum}}\overset{i-1}{\underset{k=-i+1}{\sum}}\left\{ f_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{p},\begin{bmatrix}k\\
i
\end{bmatrix}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\boldsymbol{r}_{j}\right)+f_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{p},\begin{bmatrix}k\\
-i
\end{bmatrix}^{T}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\\
\boldsymbol{s}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\boldsymbol{r}_{j}\right)\right\} 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

but this will only stand for those 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 which are inside the unit cell of the surface, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is centered at the origin.
 In order to generalize this formula, avoiding the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 inside the unit cell, we can redefine 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{i}$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}\in\mathbb{Z}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{E}_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{c}\right)=\begin{cases}
\left\{ \boldsymbol{c}\right\}  & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i=0\end{array}\\
\overset{i}{\underset{k=-i}{\bigcup}}\left\{ \boldsymbol{c}+\begin{pmatrix}i\\
k
\end{pmatrix},\boldsymbol{c}+\begin{pmatrix}-i\\
k
\end{pmatrix}\right\} \overset{i-1}{\underset{k=-i+1}{\bigcup}}\left\{ \boldsymbol{c}+\begin{pmatrix}k\\
i
\end{pmatrix},\boldsymbol{c}+\begin{pmatrix}k\\
-i
\end{pmatrix}\right\}  & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i\ge1\end{array}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{c}$
\end_inset

 is the integer coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 in basis 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Environment with hexagonal partition of space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{E}_{i}^{<6>}=\begin{cases}
\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}\right\}  & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i=0\end{array}\\
\overset{i-1}{\underset{k=0}{\bigcup}}\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}i\\
-k
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}-i\\
k
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}k\\
-i
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}-k\\
i
\end{pmatrix}\right\} \bigcup\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}i\\
-i
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}-i\\
i
\end{pmatrix}\right\}  & \iff i=1\\
\overset{i-1}{\overset{i-1}{\underset{k=1}{\bigcup}}\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}k\\
i-k
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}-k\\
k-i
\end{pmatrix}\right\} \underset{k=0}{\bigcup}}\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}i\\
-k
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}-i\\
k
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}k\\
-i
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}-k\\
i
\end{pmatrix}\right\} \bigcup\left\{ \begin{pmatrix}i\\
-i
\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}-i\\
i
\end{pmatrix}\right\}  & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i\end{array}\ge2
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can easily calculate the cardinal of each subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{i}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\#\mathcal{E}_{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i=0\end{array}\\
6i & \begin{array}{cc}
\iff & i\ge1\end{array}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


